"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 23–25
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-ezekiel-23-25-fill.py

Christological themes:
- Ch23: unfaithful bride-sisters → Christ as the faithful Bridegroom; cup of wrath taken by Christ
- Ch24: death of Ezekiel's wife (sign act) → Father not sparing the Son (Rom 8:32);
  Ezekiel as sign pointing to Christ; dumbness/opening of mouth as prophetic witness
- Ch25: four-nations judgment → nations' inclusion through Christ; Edom as type;
  universal recognition formula fulfilled in Phil 2:10-11

Every verse receives an entry per mkt-christ protocol.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL_CHRIST = {
"23": {
    "1": '<p>Chapter 23 extends the husband-wife allegory of chapter 16 to both kingdoms — Israel (Oholah) and Judah (Oholibah). The Christological trajectory of the chapter is from unfaithful wife to restored bride. The NT describes the church as the bride of Christ (Rev 19:7-9; Eph 5:25-27; 2 Cor 11:2), and the transformation from the harlot of Rev 17 to the pure bride of Rev 19 is the exact movement that Ezekiel\'s two-sisters allegory anticipates.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Two women, daughters of one mother — the covenant community originating from the same source. Christologically, the single origin of both sisters points to the unity of the one people of God who are drawn from both Israel and the nations into Christ: "there is neither Jew nor Greek... you are all one in Christ Jesus" (Gal 3:28). The Bridegroom does not have two brides but one — the one body of Christ drawn from both the old and new covenant communities.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The prostitution beginning in Egypt — the origin of the defiling alliances. Christologically, "Egypt" represents the world-system from which the covenant community is always being called out. The Exodus pattern (called out of Egypt) is the archetype of Christian conversion: "called out of darkness into his marvelous light" (1 Pet 2:9). The sin that began in Egypt is ended by the one who was himself called out of Egypt (Matt 2:15 citing Hos 11:1: "Out of Egypt I called my son").</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>Oholah and Oholibah: my wives</strong>: Both sisters were YHWH\'s wives — the covenant relationship was real with both kingdoms. That the husband is YHWH and the relationship is a marriage-covenant points to Christ as the ultimate fulfillment of the bridegroom role. Jesus explicitly identifies himself as the bridegroom: "The bridegroom is with them" (Mark 2:19-20); the parable of the ten virgins (Matt 25:1-13) has Christ as the bridegroom for whom the church waits.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Oholah (Samaria) lusted after the Assyrians. The first sister\'s infidelity with the first imperial power. Christologically, the pattern of seeking security in human imperial power rather than in YHWH is the pattern that Christ breaks: "my kingdom is not of this world" (John 18:36). The Messiah does not arrive as an imperial force but as the servant-king (Phil 2:6-8), refusing the worldly-power temptation that both kingdoms succumbed to.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Governors and commanders — desirable young men, all of them. The glamour of imperial military power as the object of covenant betrayal. Christologically, the contrast is with the Suffering Servant: "he had no form or majesty that we should look at him, no beauty that we should desire him" (Isa 53:2). The one Israel should have desired had no imperial glamour; the one Israel desired instead of him had every appearance of worldly power.</p>',
    "7": '<p>All the idols of Assyria as part of the covenant betrayal. The entanglement of political alliance with religious compromise — accepting the Assyrian gods alongside the Assyrian army. Christologically, the idols of the nations are the alternative objects of worship that compete with Christ. Paul\'s confrontation with Athenian idolatry (Acts 17:22-31) ends with the announcement of the one through whom YHWH will judge the world — the universal alternative to all the idols.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The Egyptian prostitution continued from youth — the layering of successive apostasies without abandonment of the first. The cumulative weight of covenant failure is the condition that makes a new covenant necessary. Christ comes not to patch the old system but to establish an entirely new one: "the new has come" (2 Cor 5:17); "he abolishes the first in order to establish the second" (Heb 10:9).</p>',
    "9": '<p>YHWH handed Oholah over to her Assyrian lovers who destroyed her. The 722 BCE destruction of Samaria as covenant judgment. Christologically, the divine handing-over is the same language used in Romans 8:32 in the opposite direction: "he who did not spare his own Son but gave him up (<em>paredōken</em>) for us all." The handing over of the covenant people to their enemies is reversed in the handing over of the Son for the covenant people.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Oholah executed — her nakedness uncovered, sons and daughters taken, herself slain with the sword. The complete covenant judgment becomes the cautionary example for her sister. Christologically, the executed covenant people is the condition that makes the resurrection pattern necessary: "unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit" (John 12:24). The death of Oholah is not the end but the pattern of dying that leads to resurrection-life.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Oholibah (Jerusalem) saw all this and was more corrupt than her sister. The witness to judgment that failed to produce repentance — the perversity of increasing sin in the face of observed consequences. Christologically, this is the hardening of heart that Jesus encounters in his own ministry: "though he had done so many signs before them, they still did not believe in him" (John 12:37). The hardening that Ezekiel diagnoses leads to the judgment that makes the new creation necessary.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Oholibah lusted after the Assyrians — governors, commanders, horsemen, all of them handsome young men. The same infatuation with imperial military power that destroyed her sister. Christologically, the imperial-power temptation of the second wilderness trial (Matt 4:8-10) — "all these kingdoms I will give you" — is the Oholibah-temptation. Christ\'s refusal is the covenantal faithfulness that both sisters failed to display.</p>',
    "13": '<p>YHWH saw that both were defiled in the same way. The divine omniscience that misses nothing — both the public infidelity and the hidden sins are equally visible to YHWH. "Nothing is hidden that will not be made manifest" (Luke 8:17). The comprehensive divine knowledge that condemns is the same knowledge that enables the comprehensive divine grace: Christ knows every sin of the bride and loves her despite it (Rev 2-3).</p>',
    "14": '<p>Oholibah increased her prostitution upon seeing the carved images of Babylonian warriors on the wall. The visual desire — seeing the Babylonian murals and wanting what they represented. The lust of the eyes (1 John 2:16) as the mechanism of covenant betrayal. Christologically, Christ redirects vision: "blessed are the pure in heart, for they shall see God" (Matt 5:8). The vision of Babylon\'s walls gives way to the vision of the Holy City (Rev 21:10-27) for those whose eyes have been purified.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The detailed Babylonian attire — turbans, flowing robes. The visual allure of Babylonian imperial splendor. In Revelation 18:16, Babylon is described in exactly these terms: "clothed in fine linen, in purple and scarlet, adorned with gold, with jewels, and with pearls." The contrast is the bride of Christ in Rev 19:8 clothed in fine linen that represents the righteous deeds of the saints — beautiful by the gift of grace rather than by imperial self-decoration.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Desire at the sight — messengers sent to Babylon. The movement from visual desire to diplomatic action. The Christological reversal: Christ comes to the spiritually destitute rather than waiting to be sent for. "While we were still sinners, Christ died for us" (Rom 5:8) — the movement is always from God toward the people, not the people sending for God as a political convenience.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The Babylonians coming to her bed, defiling her, then turning from her in disgust. The broken relationship — the allies-turned-disgusted follows the pattern of every idolatrous relationship. The satisfaction that the world\'s alliances promise but do not deliver is the background for Christ\'s offer: "whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again" (John 4:14). The Babylonian alliance creates disgust; the divine covenant creates eternal satisfaction.</p>',
    "18": '<p>YHWH\'s soul recoiled from Oholibah as it had from Oholah. The divine emotional withdrawal — not abandonment but grief. The prophetic tradition of divine pathos (Hos 11:8: "How can I give you up, O Ephraim?") is the background for Christ\'s weeping over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41-44) — the same grief that Ezekiel\'s YHWH experiences is embodied in the incarnate Son who weeps at the city\'s approaching destruction.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Increased prostitution recalling the days of her youth in Egypt. The regression to the original pattern — spiritual recidivism. The NT pattern of spiritual regression is addressed by the letter of Hebrews (Heb 6:4-6; 10:26-31) — the repeated warning not to fall away from Christ back to the patterns that Christ has replaced. The regression to Egyptian apostasy is the paradigm for falling away from the new covenant.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The explicit Egyptian-lust description. The raw animal dimension of the Egypt-desire — the purely physical, non-covenantal, non-personal character of the alternative. Christologically, the contrast is with the covenant love that Christ offers: intimate, personal, faithful — not the anonymous power-lust that Egypt represented but the named, face-to-face knowledge of John 10:3 (the shepherd "calls his own sheep by name").</p>',
    "21": '<p>The reviving of the lewdness of youth — the return to the beginning of the cycle. The spiritual return to the starting point of covenant failure. Christologically, Jesus does not merely return people to their original state but transforms them: "behold, I am making all things new" (Rev 21:5). The new covenant is not a return to the Egyptian beginning but a new creation that transcends the entire old cycle.</p>',
    "22": '<p>YHWH turns Oholibah\'s lovers against her as instruments of judgment. The lovers become the executioners — the political allies become the destroyers. Christologically, the reversal of all human alliances under divine judgment points to the one relationship that cannot be reversed: "who shall separate us from the love of Christ?" (Rom 8:35). Where every political alliance ends in betrayal, the covenant love of Christ is indestructible.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The Babylonian coalition gathering against Jerusalem. The multinational character of the invading force mirrors the multinational character of the final gathering in Revelation — but there the nations gather not for judgment but for worship: "a great multitude that no one could number, from every nation, from all tribes and peoples and languages, standing before the throne and before the Lamb" (Rev 7:9).</p>',
    "24": '<p>Battle equipment, chariots, wagons, the assembly of peoples — judgment by military force. The juridical framing of the military assault: the nations as YHWH\'s judicial instruments. Christologically, the cross is also a juridical act — the divine court passing sentence on sin through the crucifixion. But at the cross, the innocent bears the sentence of the guilty, reversing the normal judicial logic.</p>',
    "25": '<p>Divine jealousy and the judicial mutilation. The jealousy of YHWH for his covenant (Exod 20:5) is the love-side of the wrath. Christologically, the divine jealousy that judges sin is the same divine love that gave the Son: the God who is "jealous" for his people is the same God who "so loved the world that he gave his only Son" (John 3:16). Jealousy and love are not opposites in the covenant but two dimensions of the same covenantal commitment.</p>',
    "26": '<p>Stripping of clothing and jewelry — the reversal of the bridal adornment. The stripping of ch23 parallels the stripping of ch16:39 and both point to Christ\'s stripping on the cross (Matt 27:28, 35): the garments taken by the soldiers, the nakedness endured by the sinless one, so that the guilty might be re-robed in righteousness. "He was stripped that we might be clothed" (cf. 2 Cor 5:21).</p>',
    "27": '<p>The end of the lewdness and the cessation of longing for Egypt. The judgment\'s remedial purpose — ending the pattern by confronting it with ultimate consequences. Christologically, the cross has the same remedial purpose: not merely punishing sin but ending its power over those who trust Christ. "Our old self was crucified with him in order that the body of sin might be brought to nothing, so that we would no longer be enslaved to sin" (Rom 6:6).</p>',
    "28": '<p>Given into the hand of those she hates — the former lovers turned enemies. The complete isolation of the unfaithful bride. Christologically, the opposite: Christ, given into the hands of those who hate him (Luke 9:44), does so voluntarily and redemptively — "into your hands I commit my spirit" (Luke 23:46). The handing-over that destroys Oholibah is the handing-over that saves those Oholibah represents, because the Son takes the place of the guilty bride.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Taken with hatred, stripped of all earnings — total economic stripping. The reversal of all the accumulated prosperity of the monarchy period. Christologically, Christ "became poor, so that you by his poverty might become rich" (2 Cor 8:9) — the inverse economic transaction of the cross reverses the stripping-judgment into gift-giving.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The judgment because of the going-after-nations and the defilement with their idols. The covenantal accusation stated clearly: covenant infidelity with pagan nations brought covenant judgment. Christologically, the diagnostic clarity of this verse is the background for Paul\'s argument that all have sinned (Rom 3:23) — the catalogued infidelity of Israel and Judah demonstrates that no covenant community achieves righteousness by its own performance.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Walking in the way of the sister — drinking her cup. The passing of the judgment-cup from the destroyed northern kingdom to the surviving southern kingdom. Christologically, the cup of YHWH\'s wrath that Jerusalem must drink is the same cup Jesus faces in Gethsemane (Matt 26:39-42). He asks if the cup can pass from him; unlike Jerusalem (who drank by necessity), he drinks voluntarily — "not my will but yours be done."</p>',
    "32": '<p>The cup of Samaria: deep and wide, holding much. The comprehensiveness of the judgment cup. Christologically, the depth and width of the cup Christ drank on behalf of the covenant people is the measure of his love: "the breadth and length and height and depth... the love of Christ that surpasses knowledge" (Eph 3:18-19). The cup\'s dimensions become the dimensions of grace.</p>',
    "33": '<p>Drunkenness and desolation — the cup of horror and destruction of Samaria. The cup-imagery as total disorientation and devastation. Christologically, Christ\'s "my God, my God, why have you forsaken me" (Matt 27:46; Ps 22:1) is the cry of one who has drunk the cup of desolation — the horror of divine abandonment experienced in full so that those for whom he drinks it need never experience it.</p>',
    "34": '<p>Drinking the cup, draining it, gnawing the potsherds, tearing one\'s own breasts. The complete consumption of judgment — nothing left untouched. Christologically, Christ\'s atoning work is complete: "It is finished" (<em>tetelestai</em>, John 19:30) — the cup entirely drained, the judgment fully absorbed. No further cup remains for those who trust him: "there is therefore now no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus" (Rom 8:1).</p>',
    "35": '<p>"Because you forgot me and cast me behind your back, you yourself must bear your lewdness and your prostitutions." The root sin: forgetting YHWH. The covenantal failure of memory and regard. Christologically, the Lord\'s Supper is instituted as the counter-memorial: "do this in remembrance of me" (1 Cor 11:24-25) — the Eucharist as the practice of not forgetting, the regular covenantal re-remembering that Israel consistently failed to maintain.</p>',
    "36": '<p>YHWH commands Ezekiel to judge both sisters and declare their abominations. The combined indictment of both kingdoms as a whole. Christologically, the universal scope of the indictment — both the northern and southern kingdoms, representing all of Israel — is the background for Paul\'s universal conclusion: "all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God" (Rom 3:23), requiring the universal redemption available "through the redemption that is in Christ Jesus" (Rom 3:24).</p>',
    "37": '<p>Adultery and blood on hands — murder of children. The twin crimes: covenant infidelity and the sacrifice of covenant children. Christologically, Christ addresses both: his blood cleanses from all sin (1 John 1:7) including the sin of bloodguilt; and his atoning death provides the sacrifice that ends the need for child sacrifice — "he gave himself up as a fragrant offering and sacrifice to God" (Eph 5:2).</p>',
    "38": '<p>Defiling the sanctuary on the same day as the child sacrifice. The liturgical abomination: blood-stained hands in the sanctuary. This is the situation that the author of Hebrews addresses when describing Christ\'s priestly ministry: he entered not with "the blood of goats and calves but with his own blood, thus securing an eternal redemption" (Heb 9:12) — the sanctuary purified not by further sacrifices but by the one sufficient sacrifice.</p>',
    "39": '<p>Children killed then entering the sanctuary — the same day. The juxtaposition of violence and worship. Christologically, Christ unifies what Israel split: in him, the sacrifice is the entrance into the sanctuary, not a desecration of it. Hebrews 10:19-22: "we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus... as the great priest over the house of God."</p>',
    "40": '<p>Sending for men from far away — diplomatic messaging and preparation for the visiting lover-kings. The elaborate international courtship of foreign powers as covenant betrayal. Christologically, the movement is reversed: it is God who sends across the cosmic distance — "in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son" (Heb 1:2), "God sending his own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh" (Rom 8:3). The sending that Israel did toward foreign powers, the Father does toward the people.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The couch, the table spread, the incense and oil — YHWH\'s gifts used as preparation for foreign diplomatic encounters. The sacred gifts made into secular-diplomatic props. Christologically, the re-consecration of these gifts is the Eucharist: the bread and cup (table spread), the fragrant offering (incense) — all restored to their proper covenantal context in Christ\'s new-covenant meal.</p>',
    "42": '<p>The carefree crowd with bracelets and beautiful crowns. The festivity of the pagan diplomatic encounter. Christologically, festivity itself is not condemned but re-consecrated: the wedding feast of the Lamb (Rev 19:9: "blessed are those who are invited to the marriage supper of the Lamb") is the ultimate feast, where the celebration is of the covenant restored rather than the covenant betrayed.</p>',
    "43": '<p>The worn-out woman continuing to prostitute herself. The exhaustion of covenant infidelity — the cycle that never satisfies and never ends by itself. Christologically, the Samaritan woman at the well (John 4:7-26) is the Oholah/Oholibah figure in the Gospels: five husbands and a current non-husband, the thirst that Jacob\'s well cannot quench. Christ offers water that ends the cycle permanently.</p>',
    "44": '<p>Going to the loose woman. The community pattern — everyone going to the prostitute as to a common woman. The normalization of covenant infidelity. Christologically, this normalization of sin is what Paul says Christ came to break: "you were washed, you were sanctified, you were justified in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ and by the Spirit of our God" (1 Cor 6:11) — the "formerly" of the community that was like Oholah and Oholibah.</p>',
    "45": '<p>Righteous men judging with the judgment for adulteresses and for women who shed blood. The legal-community judgment. Christologically, the community judgment of the covenant-breaking city anticipates the final judgment before the Son of Man: "when the Son of Man comes in his glory, and all the angels with him, then he will sit on his glorious throne. Before him will be gathered all the nations" (Matt 25:31-32). The prophetic judgment of Ezekiel 23 is the temporal expression of the eschatological judgment.</p>',
    "46": '<p>The assembly brought up against them — terror and plunder. The divine command for the punishing assembly. Christologically, the gathered assembly of judgment in Ezekiel 23 is inverted in the NT gathering: "For where two or three are gathered in my name, there am I among them" (Matt 18:20). The fearful assembly of judgment becomes the joyful assembly of the new covenant community gathered around Christ.</p>',
    "47": '<p>The stoning and sword execution of both sisters. The double death sentence of both kingdoms. Christologically, death is the sentence that Christ absorbs: "he himself bore our sins in his body on the tree" (1 Pet 2:24). The double execution of both covenant kingdoms is the double condemnation that one innocent person absorbs on the cross, freeing those who trust him from their own condemnation.</p>',
    "48": '<p>Removing lewdness from the land so that all women might be instructed not to do as they had done. The instructive purpose of the judgment — the lesson for the nations. Christologically, the removal of lewdness from the land is the negative form of what the sanctifying work of the Spirit accomplishes: "it is God who works in you, both to will and to work for his good pleasure" (Phil 2:13). The instruction that judgment provides by fear, the Spirit provides by transformation.</p>',
    "49": '<p><strong>Bearing the penalty of sinful idolatry — and knowing YHWH</strong>: "They shall bear the penalty of your sinful idolatry, and you shall know that I am the Lord YHWH." The closing recognition formula after the double sentence of both sisters. The bearing of penalty is what makes the knowing-YHWH possible. Christologically, Christ bears the penalty (Isa 53:4-5: "he has borne our griefs... he was wounded for our transgressions") so that the knowing of YHWH might be restored: "this is eternal life, that they know you, the only true God" (John 17:3). The penalty-bearing and the knowing-YHWH are causally linked through the cross.</p>'
},
"24": {
    "1": '<p><strong>The precise date of the siege</strong>: The exact date marking the beginning of Nebuchadnezzar\'s siege of Jerusalem. Christologically, this precision of divine timing is the background for the "fullness of time" principle: "when the fullness of time had come, God sent forth his Son" (Gal 4:4). YHWH knows the exact moment that his redemptive acts occur — the precision of Ezekiel 24:1 (9th year, 10th month, 10th day) points to the divine mastery of history that culminates in the cross "at the right time" (Rom 5:6: "while we were still weak, at the right time Christ died for the ungodly").</p>',
    "2": '<p>Write down the name of this day — the command to record the moment. The accountability of the prophetic word to historical verification. Christologically, the historical specificity of the incarnation is integral to the gospel: "under Pontius Pilate" in the creed, the exact date-markers of Luke 3:1-2 (the 15th year of Tiberius, etc.). The gospel is not myth but dated historical event, just as Ezekiel\'s oracle is dated historical prophecy.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The allegory of the rusty pot for the rebellious house. The sign-act mode of prophetic communication — enacted metaphor rather than verbal description alone. Christologically, Jesus consistently uses this same enacted-metaphor mode: cleansing the temple (John 2:14-17), cursing the fig tree (Mark 11:12-21), washing the disciples\' feet (John 13:1-17). The prophetic tradition of enacted signs culminates in the incarnation itself — the ultimate sign-act of God acting within history.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Gathering the pieces into the pot — the choice pieces, thigh and shoulder. The best portions of the covenant community gathered into the vessel of judgment. Christologically, the gathering into the pot of judgment is the gathering into Christ in reverse: where the judgment-pot gathers the people to destruction, Christ gathers the scattered people to salvation (John 11:52: "to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad").</p>',
    "5": '<p>Pile on the wood, kindle the fire, boil the bones within it. The thorough cooking — nothing spared. The fire under the pot is YHWH\'s judgment. Christologically, "our God is a consuming fire" (Heb 12:29, citing Deut 4:24) — the fire of divine holiness cannot be avoided. But Christ has absorbed this fire: "God made him who had no sin to be sin for us" (2 Cor 5:21), taking the full heat of the divine judgment.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>The bloody city with its rust</strong>: The rusty pot — the accumulated bloodguilt and moral contamination. The piece-by-piece removal without lot-casting: no preferences, all equally condemned. Christologically, the impartiality of the judgment (no lot-casting to spare any piece) corresponds to Paul\'s "all have sinned" (Rom 3:23) — there is no untainted piece in the covenant pot. This universal condemnation is the necessary precondition for the universal offer of grace.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Blood poured on bare rock, not covered with earth. The open, unatoned blood of injustice. Christologically, Abel\'s blood cried from the ground (Gen 4:10) — pointing to a blood that cries louder still. Hebrews 12:24 says Jesus\'s blood "speaks a better word than the blood of Abel." The uncovered blood of Jerusalem\'s injustice is addressed by the covered blood of Christ\'s sacrifice: "the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin" (1 John 1:7).</p>',
    "8": '<p>Blood put on bare rock to provoke wrath — the open accusation. The blood as the permanent visible accusation before YHWH. Christologically, Christ\'s blood serves the opposite function: it silences the accusation rather than amplifying it. "The accuser of our brothers" is overcome "by the blood of the Lamb" (Rev 12:10-11). Where the open blood of Jerusalem\'s injustice cries for vengeance, the blood of Christ cries "forgiveness."</p>',
    "9": '<p>YHWH himself makes the pile great — the divine amplification of the judgment. The intensification of the fire: not just natural consequence but active divine judgment. Christologically, the divine initiative in judgment corresponds to the divine initiative in salvation: "he chose us in him before the foundation of the world" (Eph 1:4). The same divine "I myself" (<em>va\'ani</em>) who intensifies the judgment is the one who said "I myself will seek my lost sheep" (Ezek 34:11; Luke 15:4).</p>',
    "10": '<p>Heap on the wood, kindle the fire, cook the meat thoroughly — the complete consumption of the judgment. The thoroughness of the cooking mirrors the completeness required for atonement. Christologically, the completeness of Christ\'s atoning work: "by a single offering he has perfected for all time those who are being sanctified" (Heb 10:14). The thorough cooking of judgment corresponds to the thorough work of the cross.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The empty pot placed on the coals — the purification of the vessel after its contents are consumed. Even the structure requires purification after judgment. Christologically, the new creation is not merely the refilling of the old pot but its complete purification: "the first things have passed away... behold, I am making all things new" (Rev 21:4-5). The empty pot on the coals is the purified structure ready for new contents.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The rust that does not come out with fire — the unremovable contamination. The limit of purification-by-judgment: even intense fire cannot clean what only grace can address. Christologically, the inadequacy of judgment-alone purification is precisely the point of Hebrews 10:1-4: "it is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sins." The persistent rust requires what fire alone cannot provide — the priestly intercession of Christ who "always lives to make intercession" (Heb 7:25).</p>',
    "13": '<p>The filth of lewdness — purification attempted but not achieved. YHWH tried to purify through partial judgments but the contamination remained. Christologically, this is the diagnosis that makes the incarnation necessary: human moral failure cannot be remedied by escalating external discipline. The new covenant writes the law on the heart (Jer 31:33) — internal transformation rather than external correction — accomplished by the Spirit poured out through Christ\'s redemptive work.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>The irreversible word</strong>: "I will not hold back, I will not spare, I will not relent." The triple non-relenting of divine judgment. Christologically, this absolute divine commitment to judgment is what makes substitutionary atonement necessary. God cannot simply overlook sin without injustice — the triple negation of v.14 is the righteousness that the cross satisfies. Romans 3:25-26: God presented Christ as a propitiation "to show his righteousness" — so that he might be just and the justifier of those who trust Jesus.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A word comes to Ezekiel concerning his wife. The transition from the pot-allegory to the most personal oracle in the entire book. Christologically, the move from cosmic judgment (the city) to intimate loss (the wife) mirrors the incarnation\'s move from cosmic lordship to personal sacrifice: "the Word became flesh and dwelt among us" (John 1:14). The divine commitment is not merely juridical-abstract but personally costly.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>The desire of your eyes taken with a plague</strong>: YHWH will take Ezekiel\'s wife suddenly and Ezekiel must not mourn. The most costly prophetic sign-act in scripture — the prophet\'s own beloved as the instrument of divine communication. Christologically, this is the most direct preparation for "he did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all" (Rom 8:32). The Father who commanded Ezekiel not to mourn publicly is the Father who gave the Son he loved supremely. Both are acts of love made costly by love\'s own depth.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The prohibition on mourning — no sighing, no weeping, no mourning-bread. The counter-cultural command to withhold all outward grief. Christologically, the voluntary self-restriction of love — the Father who did not intervene to save the Son, the Son who prayed "not my will but yours be done" (Luke 22:42) — is foreshadowed in Ezekiel\'s obedient non-mourning. The discipline of love that can contain its grief for a greater purpose is the model of sacrificial love.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Ezekiel speaks to the people in the morning; his wife dies in the evening; in the morning he does not mourn. The three-beat sequence: prophecy → death → continued ministry without mourning. The Christological parallel is the resurrection pattern: crucifixion → death → resurrection and continued ministry. The prophet who continues to function after the loss that should have broken him is the sign of One who continues to intercede after the death that seemed to end everything.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The people ask: "Will you not tell us what these things mean for us?" — the standard prophetic sign-act question. The people\'s inquiry is always the sign-act\'s purpose: to prompt the question that allows the divine word to be received. Christologically, Jesus\'s actions consistently prompt this same question: "What is this? A new teaching with authority!" (Mark 1:27). The signs create the space for explanation; the explanation points to the greater reality.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Ezekiel reports that the word of YHWH came to him. The prophetic self-attribution — not his own imagination but divine communication. Christologically, Christ\'s words have the same self-attribution but at a higher level: "the word that you hear is not mine but the Father\'s who sent me" (John 14:24). The prophetic "thus says YHWH" becomes the Son\'s "my Father says" — same divine authority, different degree of intimacy.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>The sanctuary as the people\'s "desire of their eyes"</strong>: YHWH will profane his sanctuary, the pride and strength of the people, the desire of their eyes and the longing of their souls. Ezekiel\'s wife = the temple. The destruction of the most cherished covenantal institution mirrors the death of the most cherished personal relationship. Christologically, Jesus is "greater than the temple" (Matt 12:6) and his body is the true temple (John 2:19-22). The profaned physical temple is replaced by the living temple of his body and the community gathered in him (1 Cor 3:16; Eph 2:19-22).</p>',
    "22": '<p>The people will do as Ezekiel did: not cover the lips, not eat mourning-bread. The sign-act applied to the whole community. The community of non-mourning is not a community of no-feeling but of overwhelmed incapacity. Christologically, the church lives in a similar between-time: the sanctuary (Christ\'s body) appears to have been removed, yet the disciples do not mourn in the world\'s way. Paul\'s "we do not grieve as others do who have no hope" (1 Thess 4:13) is the resurrection-form of this non-mourning.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Turbans on heads, sandals on feet — the inverted signs (not removed as in mourning but maintained). The normal world-order continuing in the midst of incomprehensible loss. Christologically, the disciples at Pentecost continue normal life activities (they were "devoting themselves to prayer" while waiting, Acts 1:14) in the period between the ascension and the Spirit\'s coming. The between-time requires sustained presence and prayer rather than paralytic mourning.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>Ezekiel as the sign</strong>: "Ezekiel shall be a sign to you; according to all that he has done you shall do." The prophet whose life is the message — not just the medium but the content of the communication. Christologically, Jesus is the ultimate sign: "the sign of the Son of Man" (Matt 24:30); "greater than Jonah" (Matt 12:41). But where Jonah and Ezekiel were signs pointing beyond themselves, Christ is the sign that is the reality — the signifier who is also the signified.</p>',
    "25": '<p>When YHWH takes the stronghold, the glory, the desire of their eyes and the longing of their souls — sons and daughters also — the fugitive comes. The comprehensive loss that precedes the opening of the mouth. Christologically, the comprehensive loss of the crucifixion — the disciples\' despair on Good Friday — is the necessary precondition for the Easter joy. "Unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit" (John 12:24).</p>',
    "26": '<p>The fugitive who comes to open the ears — the news-bearer whose arrival unlocks the prophetic voice. The fugitive is the messenger of the completed judgment who liberates Ezekiel from his constrained speech. Christologically, the resurrection is the event that liberates the disciples from their post-crucifixion silence: "the disciples were glad when they saw the Lord" (John 20:20); Peter who denied three times became the one who preached to three thousand at Pentecost. The fugitive\'s news transforms silence into proclamation.</p>',
    "27": '<p><strong>The opening of the mouth</strong>: On the day the fugitive arrives, Ezekiel\'s mouth is opened and he is silent no more. The end of the constrained speech that has characterized the judgment period. Christologically, this is the resurrection-unlocking of testimony. The disciples who were hidden "for fear of the Jews" (John 20:19) have their mouth opened by the risen Christ: "Peace be with you. As the Father has sent me, even so I am sending you" (John 20:21). The great commission is the eschatological opening of the prophetic mouth that Ezekiel 24:27 anticipates.</p>'
},
"25": {
    "1": '<p>The oracle-word of YHWH introducing the four-nations section. The oracles against surrounding nations (chs 25-32) are framed within YHWH\'s universal sovereignty. Christologically, this section grounds the universality of Christ\'s lordship: "all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me" (Matt 28:18) — not just authority over Israel but over Ammon, Moab, Edom, Philistia, Tyre, Sidon, and Egypt. The Great Commission that follows from "all authority" has its prophetic foundation in the nations-oracles of the prophets.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Face set toward the Ammonites — the divine addressing of Israel\'s eastern neighbor. The prophetic oracle directed specifically to Ammon. Christologically, the specification of nations is the background for the universal mission: "Go and make disciples of all nations (<em>panta ta ethnē</em>)" (Matt 28:19) — precisely the nations that the OT prophets addressed in judgment are the nations the NT mission addresses with the gospel. Ammon (modern Jordan) is included in the universal scope of the new-covenant mission.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Ammon said "Aha!" over YHWH\'s sanctuary when it was profaned, over Israel when it was made desolate, over Judah when it went into exile. Malicious joy at the covenant people\'s ruin. Christologically, the nations who gloated over Israel\'s destruction are the nations Paul describes in Romans 11:18: "do not boast over the branches." The warning against gentile arrogance at Israel\'s partial hardening assumes that the same spirit that animated Ammon could animate the churches Paul addresses.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Given to the people of the east as a possession, their encampments and dwelling places established in Ammon. The historical judgment on Ammon — taken over by the eastern desert peoples. Christologically, the judgment on those who rejected the covenant sign (the temple\'s desolation) is the background for the warning of Hebrews 10:29: "how much worse punishment will be deserved by the one who has trampled underfoot the Son of God." Greater privilege (knowing the covenant sign) entails greater accountability.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Rabbah becomes a pasture for camels and Ammon a fold for flocks — the reversal from urban civilization to pastoral wasteland. The recognition formula: "you shall know that I am YHWH." Christologically, this forced recognition of YHWH through judgment anticipates the voluntary recognition through faith. Every unwilling acknowledgment of YHWH\'s sovereignty in the OT points toward the willing acknowledgment that Paul describes: "at the name of Jesus every knee should bow... and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord" (Phil 2:10-11).</p>',
    "6": '<p>Ammon clapped hands and stamped feet and rejoiced with full contempt over Israel. The physical expression of malicious joy — body language of contempt. Christologically, the contempt of the nations for the covenant people is most intensely expressed in the passion narrative: "they mocked him, saying Hail, King of the Jews!" (Matt 27:29). The clapping and stamping of Ammon is the prototype of the soldiers\' contemptuous mockery of the King who was simultaneously condemned and crowned.</p>',
    "7": '<p>YHWH stretches out his hand against Ammon, gives them as plunder, cuts them off from the peoples. The divine counter-action against those who rejoiced at the covenant people\'s ruin. Christologically, the nations who were cut off from the peoples anticipate Paul\'s argument: "if you were cut from what is by nature a wild olive tree, and grafted, contrary to nature, into a cultivated olive tree, how much more will these, the natural branches, be grafted back into their own olive tree" (Rom 11:24). Cutting off and grafting in are both within YHWH\'s sovereign purpose.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Moab says "the house of Judah is like all the other nations." Moab\'s theological claim — denying Israel\'s covenant distinctiveness. Christologically, the denial of covenantal election is addressed by Paul in Romans 9-11: yes, all nations have sinned equally (Rom 3:23), but the gospel is "to the Jew first and also to the Greek" (Rom 1:16) — not because of inherent superiority but because of covenant history that culminates in the Messiah who comes from Israel (Rom 9:5).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The flank of Moab exposed from its border cities. The geographic vulnerability of Moab under divine judgment. Christologically, the exposing of what seemed secure — the border fortifications of Moab\'s identity — is the pattern of the gospel\'s encounter with every human security structure: "every lofty opinion raised against the knowledge of God" (2 Cor 10:5) taken captive to Christ.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Given to the sons of the East as Ammon was — the same fate shared by both Transjordanian kingdoms. The equalization of judgment across related nations. Christologically, the equal treatment of Ammon and Moab prepares for Paul\'s equal treatment of Jew and Greek: the same Lord "is Lord of all, bestowing his riches on all who call on him" (Rom 10:12) — the same Lord who judges all equally is the same Lord who saves all equally who trust him.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Judgments executed on Moab — the recognition formula closes the Moab oracle. "They shall know that I am YHWH." The forced recognition that Moab denied (v.8: "like all the other nations") is now imposed through judgment. Christologically, the ultimate forced recognition is the judgment at the end of the age: "every knee shall bow" (Phil 2:10) — both those who denied God\'s lordship and those who affirmed it will acknowledge it. The difference is whether the acknowledgment comes through faith now or through judgment then.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Edom acted revengefully against the house of Judah and incurred grievous guilt by taking revenge. Edom\'s specific crime: active revenge rather than passive schadenfreude. Christologically, Edom (as Esau, the elder twin who lost the blessing to Jacob/Israel) represents the principle of human-natural claim against divine election. Paul uses Esau/Edom explicitly: "Jacob I loved, but Esau I hated" (Rom 9:13 citing Mal 1:2-3) — the election of grace that bypasses natural precedence is the same election that chose the younger Son of David from Bethlehem over all the greater powers of his age.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Judgment on Edom from Teman to Dedan, by the sword. The geographic totality of Edom\'s judgment. Christologically, the Edomite territory (Idumea) became the region from which Herod the Great came — the Edomite king who sought to kill the infant Messiah (Matt 2:16-18). The ancient enmity between Esau/Edom and Jacob/Israel reaches its climax in Herod\'s massacre of the innocents, and is finally resolved when the one who came to save Esau\'s children as well as Jacob\'s (cf. v.53\'s inclusion of Sodom) completes his redemptive work.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>Judgment through Israel</strong>: YHWH\'s vengeance on Edom will come through the hand of his people Israel. Unique among the four oracles: Edom\'s judgment is mediated through Israel. Christologically, the ultimate reversal of Edom-over-Israel (Esau\'s birthright, the Edomite kings listed in Gen 36 before any Israelite king) comes through the Israelite Messiah. The Son of David from Jacob\'s line is the fulfillment of the promise that "the elder will serve the younger" (Gen 25:23; Rom 9:12).</p>',
    "15": '<p>Philistia acted with perpetual enmity (<em>eivat olam</em>) and took revenge with scorn. The "perpetual enmity" reaching back to the earliest Israel-Philistia conflicts echoes the primal enmity of Genesis 3:15: "I will put enmity (<em>eivah</em>) between you and the woman, and between your offspring and her offspring." Christologically, the perpetual enmity that the seed of the serpent maintains against the covenant people is resolved by the one seed of the woman who crushes the serpent\'s head (Rom 16:20: "the God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet").</p>',
    "16": '<p>YHWH will cut off the Cherethites and destroy the remnant of the seacoast — the complete elimination of Philistia\'s power. The Philistine pentapolis destroyed. Christologically, the overthrow of the perpetual-enmity nations through divine judgment is the negative image of the positive reconciliation that Christ effects: "he himself is our peace, who has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility" (Eph 2:14). The same hostility that animated the Philistines\' perpetual enmity is the hostility that Christ broke down on the cross.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>Great vengeance with furious rebukes — and they shall know YHWH</strong>: The strongest judgment language of the four oracles closes chapter 25. The recognition formula caps all four nations\' judgments. Christologically, the universal recognition of YHWH as the goal of all the nations-judgments points to the universal acknowledgment that Christ\'s universal lordship will produce: "at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth, and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the glory of God the Father" (Phil 2:10-11). The nations who will not acknowledge YHWH willingly are brought to acknowledgment through judgment; those who acknowledge him through faith do so joyfully in advance of that final reckoning.</p>'
}
}

